<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910722-0024</DOCNO><DOCID>910722-0024.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- General DataComm Industries:   Work Force to Be Cut 10%   For Savings of $10 Million</HL><DATE>07/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   GDC</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)</IN><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   General DataComm Industries Inc., citingworse-than-expected economic conditions, said it is cuttingits staff by 10% to save $10 million over the next year.   A spokeswoman for the Middlebury, Conn., company said thecuts will reduce the company's work force world-wide by 190,with about half the cuts coming from the company'sConnecticut manufacturing facility.</LP><TEXT>   While the most of the $10 million in savings is expectedto be gained through the staff reductions, the informationnetworks and telecommunications equipment provider said italso plans cuts in discretionary spending and variousoperational areas.   &quot;The current economic conditions in several of our worldmarkets are very tight,&quot; said Charles P. Johnson, chairmanand chief executive officer. &quot;The rise in revenues we hadanticipated in fiscal 1991 hasn't yet materialized, and withrecessionary climate in several world regions, we cannot becertain when an upturn in these economies will translate intoan increase in sales.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>